{"book": {"publisher": "Bristol Classical Press", "synopsis": "Euripides\" "Medea" is one of the greatest and most influential Greek tragedies. This book outlines the development of the Medea myth before Euripides and explores his uniquely powerful version from various angles. There are chapters on the play\'s relationship to the gender politics of fifth-century Athens, Medea\'s status as a barbarian, and the complex moral and emotional impact of her revenge. Particular attention is paid to the tragic effect of Medea\'s great monologue and the significance of her role as a divine avenger. The book ends by considering the varied and fascinating reception of Euripides\' play from antiquity to the present day.', 'language": "en", "image": "https://images.isbndb.com/covers/18/74/9780715631874.jpg", "title_long": "Euripides: Medea (Companions to Greek and Roman Tragedy)", "edition": "1", "dimensions": "Height: 8.499983 Inches, Length: 5.499989 Inches, Weight: 0.39242282636 Pounds, Width: 0.31 Inches", "dimensions_structured": {"length": {"unit": "inches", "value": 5.499989}, "width": {"unit": "inches", "value": 0.31}, "weight": {"unit": "pounds", "value": 0.39242282636}, "height": {"unit": "inches", "value": 8.499983}}, "pages": 160, "date_published": "2002-10-31", "subjects": ["Arts & Photography', 'Performing Arts', 'Theater', 'Literature & Fiction', 'Classics', 'Dramas & Plays', 'Ancient & Classical', 'History & Criticism', 'Movements & Periods', 'Ancient & Medieval Literature', 'Greek', 'Roman', 'Specialty Boutique', 'New, Used & Rental Textbooks'], 'authors": ['William Allan'], 'title": "Euripides: Medea (Companions to Greek and Roman Tragedy)", "isbn13": "9780715631874", "msrp": "0.00", "binding": "Paperback", "isbn": "071563187X", "isbn10": "071563187X"}}